'''Pierre Berault''' was a 17th-century French grammarian. A [[Society of Jesus|Jesuit monk]], Berault converted to [[Protestant Christianity|Protestantism]] in 1671 and subsequently taught [[French language|French]] in England.<ref name="Lambley">{{cite book|author=Kathleen Lambley|title=The Teaching and Cultivation of the French Language in England during Tudor and Stuart Times With an Introductory Chapter on the Preceding Period|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SBojlphoNbUC&pg=PT322|publisher=Library of Alexandria|isbn=978-1-4655-8198-3|page=322}}</ref>
==Works== * ''The Church of Rome evidently proved heretick'', 1781 * ''A New, plain, short and compleat French and English grammar'', 1688 * ''Logick, or, The key of sciences, and the Moral science, or, The way to be happy'', 1690
